Data

  • Simulated data from Coxe, S., West, S. G., & Aiken, L. S. (2009). The analysis of count data: A gentle introduction to Poisson regression and its alternatives. Journal of Personality Assessment, 91(2), 121-136.
    • case: Subject ID
    • sensation: Sensation seeking (1 to 7)
    • gender: 0 = female, 1 = male
    • y: Number of alcoholic beverages consumed on Saturday night
jpa <- read_sav("jpapoisson.sav")

Outcome

ggplot(data = jpa, aes(x = y)) + 
    geom_bar(fill = "grey50", color = "grey90")

  • The mean is 2.93
  • The variance is 8.832
  • Overdispersion is about the conditional mean and variance butâ¦
    • Does it seem like there might be overdispersion?
  • What about zeroes?
    • Are there more or fewer zeroes than a Poisson distribution with this mean should have?
# Simulate Poisson distributed data with same n and mean as data
pois_mean <- rpois(nrow(jpa), mean(jpa$y, na.rm = TRUE))
pois_mean_data <- data.frame(pois_mean)
ggplot(data = jpa, aes(x = y)) + 
    geom_bar(fill = "grey50", color = "grey90") +
    geom_bar(data = pois_mean_data, 
             aes(x = pois_mean), 
             width = 0.3, 
             fill = "black")

  • Grey bars are the observed data
    • Narrower black bars are a Poisson distribution with the same mean (2.93)
  • There are more zeroes in the data than in the Poisson distributionâ¦
    • But the mis-match is not just the zeroes, so maybe just overdispersion

sensation predicts y

Poisson regression

  • sensation4 is centered at 4 (the midpoint of the 1 to 7 scale)
  • glm() works very much like lm()
    • Additional options specify the type of GLiM
      • Here, Poisson regression (with Poisson outcome distribution and log link function) is specified by family = poisson(link = "log")
jpa <- jpa %>% mutate(sensation4 = sensation - 4)
poi <- glm(y ~ sensation4, 
           data = jpa, 
           family = poisson(link = "log"))
summary(poi)

Negative binomial regression

  • sensation4 is centered at 4 (the midpoint of the 1 to 7 scale)
  • Negative binomial regression uses the glm.nb() function from the MASS package
    • It also works similarly to lm()
    • Specify data
    • Specify outcome ~ predictor relationship
negbin <- glm.nb(data = jpa, 
                 y ~ sensation4)

Zero-inflated Poisson

  • sensation4 is centered at 4 (the midpoint of the 1 to 7 scale)
  • ZIP model uses the zeroinlf() function from pscl
    • Specify outcome ~ predictor relationship for counts
    • Vertical bar (|) then predictors for logistic portion
    • dist = "poisson" for Poisson
zip <- zeroinfl(y ~ sensation4 | sensation4, 
               data = jpa,
               dist = "poisson")
summary(zip)

Interpretation

Base models: Poisson and negative binomial

  • Poisson
    • RR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.231}\) = 1.26
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count is multiplied by 1.26
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count increases by 26 percent
  • Negative binomial
    • RR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.22}\) = 1.247
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count is multiplied by 1.247
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count increases by 24.7 percent

Zero-inflated models

  • sensation4 predicts which â0 drinksâ responses are
    • Always 0: Never drinkers
    • Could be a positive count: Drinkers who didnât drink this time
  • If they were or could be a positive count, sensation4 predicts
    • How many drinks (0 or more) they have
  • Zero-inflated Poisson
    • RR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.212}\) = 1.236
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count is multiplied by 1.236
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count increases by 23.6 percent
    • OR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{-0.115}\) = 0.891
      • Predicting excess zeroes
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted odds of excess zero is multiplied by 0.891
  • Zero-inflated negative binomial
    • RR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.235}\) = 1.264
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count is multiplied by 1.264
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count increases by 26.4 percent
    • OR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.296}\) = 1.344
      • Predicting excess zeroes
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted odds of excess zero is multiplied by 1.344

Hurdle models

  • sensation4 predicts which â0 drinksâ responses are
    • 0: Non-drinkers
    • Positive count: Drinkers
  • If they have a positive count, sensation4 predicts
    • How many drinks (1 or more) they have
  • Hurdle Poisson
    • RR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.21}\) = 1.234
      • Truncated Poisson model
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count is multiplied by 1.234
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count increases by 23.4 percent
    • OR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.218}\) = 1.243
      • Predicting positive (non-zero) counts
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted odds of positive count is multiplied by 1.243
  • Hurdle NB
    • RR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.227}\) = 1.254
      • Truncated negative binomial model
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count is multiplied by 1.254
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted count increases by 25.4 percent
    • OR = \(e^{b_1}\) = \(e^{0.218}\) = 1.243
      • Predicting positive (non-zero) counts
      • For a 1 unit increase in sensation4, the predicted odds of positive count is multiplied by 1.243

AIC

  • Can be used to compare anything, nested or not
    • But no actual test
    • Just lower is better
Model <- c("Poisson", "Negative binomial", 
           "ZIP", "ZINB", 
           "Hurdle Poisson", "Hurdle NB")
AIC <- c(AIC(poi), 
         AIC(negbin), 
         AIC(zip), 
         AIC(zinb),
         AIC(hurdle_poi),
         AIC(hurdle_nb))
aic_dat <- data.frame(Model, AIC)
aic_dat

\(R^2\) values

  • All the \(R^2\) functions we talked about only work for Poisson, overdispersed Poisson, and negative binomial
    • They donât work for zero-inflated or hurdle models
    • Error or NA
r2_mcfadden(poi)

       R2: 0.017
  adj. R2: 0.016

Predicted counts

  • Code adapted from the Atkins & Gallop (2007) article (Figure 1)
    • predprob() function from pscl package calculates predicted probabilities of count values based on the model
      • Predicted probability of each outcome value for each person
        • Not just the personâs predicted value
      • Then take the mean for each outcome value (column) using apply()
        • The 2 tells it to get the mean for each column
        • One predicted probability for each value of the outcome
      • Put those in a dataset with the possible outcome values (0 to 17)
phat.poi <- predprob(poi)
phat.poi.mn <- apply(phat.poi, 2, mean)

Class task

  • Which model best represents the data?
